**Smart Enumerations in C# using Enums**

Smart enumerations are a way to extend the functionality of enumerations in C#. They allow you to add properties and methods to your enum values, making them more flexible and reusable.

Here's an example of how to implement smart enumerations in C#:

```csharp
public enum Color
{
    Red,
    Green,
    Blue
}

public class ColorExtensions
{
    public static Color GetOppositeColor(this Color color)
    {
        switch (color)
        {
            case Color.Red:
                return Color.Green;
            case Color.Green:
                return Color.Blue;
            case Color.Blue:
                return Color.Red;
            default:
                throw new ArgumentException("Invalid color");
        }
    }

    public static string GetColorName(this Color color)
    {
        return color.ToString();
    }
}

public class Program
{
    public static void Main()
    {
        var color = Color.Red;

        var oppositeColor = color.GetOppositeColor();
        Console.WriteLine($"Opposite color of {color.GetColorName()} is {oppositeColor.GetColorName()}");

        var colorName = color.GetColorName();
        Console.WriteLine($"Color name is {colorName}");
    }
}
```

